778
01:25:20,829 --> 01:25:24,208
I don't know. She didn't tell me that.

779
01:25:25,584 --> 01:25:27,586
God.

780
01:25:29,338 --> 01:25:31,340
Okay. Okay.

781
01:25:33,759 --> 01:25:36,011
Christ.

782
01:25:36,053 --> 01:25:39,348
Why... Why did she have to take all
of the photographs? There're negatives.

783
01:25:39,431 --> 01:25:43,810
She could have taken the negatives and had
prints ofher own made. She took the negatives too.

784
01:25:44,895 --> 01:25:48,774
The hell she did. Go look for yourself.

785
01:25:52,236 --> 01:25:57,574
She can't have the
photographs and the negatives.

786
01:25:57,658 --> 01:26:01,954
They were my sons too. I should have half the
photographs, for Chrissake. What about Ruth?

787
01:26:02,037 --> 01:26:05,374
Ruth should have some of the photographs.
Marion said you'd say that. But she said no.

788
01:26:07,125 --> 01:26:11,004
Oh. Well, obviously,
she went to New York.

789
01:26:11,088 --> 01:26:13,507
I doubt it. What do you know, Eddie?

790
01:26:13,549 --> 01:26:19,471
That's the only place she could go. I even know where in
the city she is. I just can't imagine her goin'to New York.

791
01:26:19,555 --> 01:26:21,849
You don't have an imagination, Eddie.

792
01:26:23,642 --> 01:26:27,145
Christ. Aren't you planning on
getting a divorce with her anyway?

793
01:26:27,229 --> 01:26:29,523
That Marion's question,
or is that your question?

794
01:26:30,566 --> 01:26:35,028
- It's mine.
- Eddie, just stick to what Marion told you to say, okay?

795
01:26:35,112 --> 01:26:40,075
- She didn't tell me to get the photograph. That was my idea.
- Well, that was a good idea.

796
01:26:40,117 --> 01:26:43,412
- "I was thinking of Ruth."
- Yeah. I know you were.

797
01:26:46,874 --> 01:26:49,960
Thank you. You want a drink?

798
01:26:50,002 --> 01:26:54,173
No.

799
01:26:55,257 --> 01:26:57,718
What day is tomorrow, Saturday? Yeah.

800
01:26:57,759 --> 01:27:03,098
I want you out of here by tomorrow. Sunday at the
latest. That's fine. I just need a ride to the ferry.

801
01:27:03,140 --> 01:27:07,269
Alice can take you.

802
01:27:07,311 --> 01:27:11,023
What about this one? Tell it!

803
01:27:11,064 --> 01:27:14,610
I'm sorry, Ruth. I don't
know. Okay? I just...

804
01:27:14,651 --> 01:27:19,865
This is the one with Thomas in the tall
hat. Timothy is trying to reach Thomas's hat.

805
01:27:19,948 --> 01:27:25,913
Timothy can't reach Thomas's hat, 'cause Thomas is
standing on a ball. Timothy got mad and started a fight.

806
01:27:25,913 --> 01:27:29,750
Was the fight in the picture? No. The
fight was after the picture, you dummy!

807
01:27:29,875 --> 01:27:33,212
Okay. We're gonna go watch a
movie. Yes. We're gonna go. No! No!

808
01:27:33,295 --> 01:27:35,631
We're gonna go pick a
video. Yes, we are. No!

809
01:27:35,631 --> 01:27:38,759
Ruthie, stop it! No! No!

810
01:27:38,800 --> 01:27:40,761
Stop it! No!

811
01:27:40,844 --> 01:27:45,516
Oh, Alice.

812
01:27:47,643 --> 01:27:49,645
What? What have you
done to Alice, Eddie?

813
01:27:49,770 --> 01:27:52,523
I didn't do anything. She was
crying when I first got here.

814
01:27:52,648 --> 01:27:55,817
I've been asking her what's wrong,
and she won't even talk to me.

815
01:28:00,364 --> 01:28:03,158
Where's Ruthie?

816
01:28:03,200 --> 01:28:07,538
Uh, she's asleep. She was crying.

817
01:28:11,792 --> 01:28:16,004
I'm sorry, Alice, for
springing all of this on you.

818
01:28:16,088 --> 01:28:19,591
Fuck you, Ted. I appreciate
you pickin' up the slack.

819
01:28:22,636 --> 01:28:27,474
I've spent years trying to get
over my own fucked-up family.

820
01:28:27,516 --> 01:28:30,102
And I've done the
best I could with Ruth.

821
01:28:30,227 --> 01:28:33,105
No.

822
01:28:33,146 --> 01:28:37,526
No. I just can't anymore.
I'm gonna quit. I quit.

823
01:28:38,569 --> 01:28:41,405
And you should have
the decency to quit too.

824
01:28:41,530 --> 01:28:44,283
It's... It's too late for me to
quit, Alice. I just got fired.

825
01:28:44,366 --> 01:28:47,578
I never knew you were such
a superior person, Alice.

826
01:28:47,703 --> 01:28:51,164
Alice has been superior to me
all summer. Haven't you Alice?

827
01:28:51,290 --> 01:28:55,002
I "am" morally superior to
you, Eddie. I know that much.

828
01:28:55,085 --> 01:28:59,006
"Morally superior." What a concept.

829
01:28:59,131 --> 01:29:03,594
Don't you ever feel morally
superior, Eddie? Hmm? To you I do.

830
01:29:03,719 --> 01:29:08,015
Yeah. You see? Everyone feels
morally superior to someone.

831
01:29:08,098 --> 01:29:10,726
Fuck you guys.

832
01:29:10,851 --> 01:29:13,687
There goes my ride to the ferry.

833
01:29:13,729 --> 01:29:17,024
Oh, you're a smart boy, Eddie. You'll
think of someone to give you a ride.

834
01:29:22,779 --> 01:29:26,825
You want a drink?

835
01:29:26,909 --> 01:29:28,827
No, thanks.

836
01:29:28,911 --> 01:29:31,330
Oh, for Chrissake. Have a beer.

837
01:29:35,751 --> 01:29:37,753
Jesus. Look at this yard.

838
01:29:41,507 --> 01:29:46,261
Cannot believe she doesn't want
custody of her own daughter.

839
01:29:46,303 --> 01:29:49,264
What kind of mother leaves her daughter?

840
01:29:49,348 --> 01:29:52,434
I don't know her well
enough to judge her.

841
01:29:52,518 --> 01:29:54,603
Let me tell you something, Eddie.

842
01:29:54,645 --> 01:29:58,398
I don't know her well
enough to judge her either.

843
01:29:58,482 --> 01:30:01,944
Yeah, well, don't forget,
it's you she's really leaving.

844
01:30:01,985 --> 01:30:05,072
Guess she knew you pretty well.

845
01:30:06,073 --> 01:30:12,079
Well enough to judge
me, you mean? Certainly.

846
01:30:12,162 --> 01:30:16,542
But then, she's leaving
you too, isn't she, Eddie?

847
01:30:20,671 --> 01:30:24,508
You don't expect her to call you
up for a secret rendezvous, do you?

848
01:30:26,552 --> 01:30:30,264
No. I don't expect to hear
from her. No, me neither.

849
01:30:30,389 --> 01:30:33,767
Hmm. I have drawings of her.

850
01:30:35,811 --> 01:30:39,106
I drew her long ago,
before the accident.

851
01:30:40,357 --> 01:30:46,113
She was so... so incredible.
So fucking beautiful. Amazing.

852
01:30:47,155 --> 01:30:49,700
You should have known her then.

853
01:30:50,993 --> 01:30:52,995
Oh, Marion.

854
01:30:54,997 --> 01:30:57,708
She hated to pose for me.

855
01:31:01,879 --> 01:31:05,132
These are the only drawings I kept.

856
01:31:07,718 --> 01:31:10,470
I was never good enough to draw Marion.

857
01:31:10,512 --> 01:31:14,850
I didn't know how to. I didn't
have the ability, I guess.

858
01:31:19,563 --> 01:31:22,316
You want one? You can have one.

859
01:31:22,441 --> 01:31:24,443
No. Ruth should have them.

860
01:31:24,484 --> 01:31:26,904
Mmm. That's a good idea.

861
01:31:27,029 --> 01:31:31,158
You're full of good ideas, Eddie.

862
01:31:32,201 --> 01:31:34,203
Wrong cubes.

863
01:31:50,761 --> 01:31:52,721
Marion?

864
01:31:52,763 --> 01:31:55,057
Jesus, aren't you the optimist?

865
01:31:58,769 --> 01:32:01,355
Forget the light, Eddie.

866
01:32:02,481 --> 01:32:04,858
This story's better in the dark.

867
01:32:09,947 --> 01:32:13,408
What story? You told me you
asked Marion to tell it to you,

868
01:32:13,492 --> 01:32:16,787
but Marion can't handle this story.

869
01:32:16,912 --> 01:32:19,623
Turns her to stone
just thinking about it.

870
01:32:19,665 --> 01:32:23,085
Remember, you turned her to
stone just asking her about it.

871
01:32:24,086 --> 01:32:26,088
I remember.

872
01:32:27,798 --> 01:32:29,800
Go on.

873
01:32:33,387 --> 01:32:35,389
Well, here's the deal.

874
01:32:38,100 --> 01:32:42,938
Thomas had his driver's
license, but Timothy did not.

875
01:32:45,190 --> 01:32:49,528
Tommy was 17 and...
been driving for a year.

876
01:32:49,570 --> 01:32:55,409
Timmy was 15. He had only
started to take driving lessons.

877
01:32:56,451 --> 01:33:00,414
It was Ted's opinion that
Timmy, who was only learning,

878
01:33:00,497 --> 01:33:05,711
was already a more attentive
student than Thomas ever had been.

879
01:33:07,713 --> 01:33:11,967
Timmy studied the
driving manual diligently.

880
01:33:13,010 --> 01:33:16,805
He was a more patient
driver than Thomas.

881
01:33:16,847 --> 01:33:21,018
Not that Tommy was a bad
driver. Tommy was a good driver.

882
01:33:22,728 --> 01:33:26,815
He was alert, confident.

883
01:33:27,900 --> 01:33:31,445
He had excellent reflexes.

884
01:33:33,155 --> 01:33:39,119
And he was cynical enough to
assume... as Ted had instructed him...

885
01:33:40,162 --> 01:33:44,041
that every other driver is a bad driver.

886
01:33:44,124 --> 01:33:47,127
Who taught to you drive, Eddie?

887
01:33:47,169 --> 01:33:50,422
Um, my dad.

888
01:33:50,506 --> 01:33:52,925
Well, good for him.

889
01:33:53,008 --> 01:33:56,845
Tell him for me, he did an
excellent job, would you?

890
01:33:58,180 --> 01:34:00,182
Okay.

891
01:34:15,948 --> 01:34:18,659
Keep... Keep going.

892
01:34:19,743 --> 01:34:25,666
We were out west, actually, and
it was after a long day of skiing.

893
01:34:25,666 --> 01:34:29,044
"It was snowing"... a wet, thick snow.

894
01:34:31,213 --> 01:34:35,634
At 17 and 15, respectively,

895
01:34:35,676 --> 01:34:39,972
Thomas and Timothy could ski
the pants off their parents.

896
01:34:40,055 --> 01:34:45,686
That day, in fact, Ted and Marion had
retired to the bar at the ski resort...

897
01:34:45,811 --> 01:34:48,522
where they were waiting
for a very long time...

898
01:34:48,564 --> 01:34:52,401
for Thomas and Timothy to
finish their last run...

899
01:34:52,401 --> 01:34:55,988
and the last run after that.

900
01:34:56,071 --> 01:34:59,700
I get the picture. You were drunk.

901
01:35:01,618 --> 01:35:05,080
Well, that, uh...

902
01:35:05,122 --> 01:35:08,834
that was one aspect of
what would become trivial...

903
01:35:08,917 --> 01:35:13,255
in the... area of the ongoing
argument between Marion and Ted.

904
01:35:13,297 --> 01:35:19,303
I mean, Marion said that Ted was
drunk, although in his view, he wasn't.

905
01:35:19,386 --> 01:35:23,724
Marion, while not drunk, certainly had had
more to drink than she was accustomed to.

906
01:35:23,724 --> 01:35:27,936
Besides, Tommy had not been
drinking. He had his license.

907
01:35:28,020 --> 01:35:31,315
There was no disagreement as to
who among them should be the driver.

908
01:35:31,440 --> 01:35:34,443
And, brothers being brothers,

909
01:35:34,484 --> 01:35:38,572
Timmy sat beside him
in the passenger seat.

910
01:35:39,615 --> 01:35:41,700
And as for the parents,

911
01:35:41,783 --> 01:35:46,747
Ted and Marion... sat in the backseat.

912
01:35:49,708 --> 01:35:52,461
Ted and Marion began to quarrel...

913
01:35:52,503 --> 01:35:56,048
about the best route back to the hotel.

914
01:35:56,131 --> 01:36:00,093
There was gonna have to be a left
turn no matter how Tommy did it.

915
01:36:00,219 --> 01:36:04,473
So, Tommy moves into the center lane.

916
01:36:04,515 --> 01:36:07,601
It's, um, a turning lane.
It's not a passing lane.

917
01:36:07,684 --> 01:36:10,771
He puts on his blinker,

918
01:36:10,771 --> 01:36:15,651
not knowing that both lights are
covered with wet, sticky snow...

919
01:36:15,651 --> 01:36:19,780
that his father failed to clear
off at the same time his father...

920
01:36:19,780 --> 01:36:22,449
failed to clear off the rear window.

921
01:36:24,952 --> 01:36:30,874
Any cars coming up from behind Tommy's
car can't see the directional signals or...

922
01:36:30,958 --> 01:36:32,876
the brake lights or the tail lights.

923
01:36:32,960 --> 01:36:37,381
The car is not visible,

924
01:36:37,464 --> 01:36:41,426
or it's visible only at
the last second to any...

925
01:36:41,510 --> 01:36:45,347
anyone approaching from behind.

926
01:36:50,060 --> 01:36:54,982
And then, the interior of
the car is filled with light.

927
01:36:54,982 --> 01:36:58,944
- "It's the headlights from the car" coming up from behind.
- ""

928
01:37:10,664 --> 01:37:13,834
The snowplow cut the car
almost perfectly in half.

929
01:37:22,176 --> 01:37:27,931
Tommy was killed by the steering column.
Crushed his chest. Died instantly.

930
01:37:29,016 --> 01:37:32,269
And Ted...

931
01:37:32,311 --> 01:37:36,231
was trapped in the backseat
for all of 20 minutes.

932
01:37:39,151 --> 01:37:41,028
He...

933
01:37:41,153 --> 01:37:47,117
- He couldn't see Tommy, but he knew he
was dead because Marion could see him.

934
01:37:48,202 --> 01:37:51,705
She couldn't see Timmy. He
was directly in front ofher.

935
01:37:51,747 --> 01:37:56,460
Ted, however, could see that
Timmy was still breathing.

936
01:37:56,543 --> 01:38:01,423
Ted could also see that the
snowplow, as it cut the car in half,

937
01:38:01,465 --> 01:38:05,511
also cut Timmy's left
leg off at the thigh.

938
01:38:12,935 --> 01:38:17,231
Timothy Cole bled to death
of a severed femoral artery.

939
01:38:21,318 --> 01:38:24,738
Marion knew that Tommy was dead,

940
01:38:24,780 --> 01:38:27,908
but only that Timmy had been
carried from the wreckage,

941
01:38:27,950 --> 01:38:31,411
hopefully... to the hospital.

942
01:38:32,454 --> 01:38:35,874
And then Marion,

943
01:38:35,958 --> 01:38:38,794
she sees Timmy's shoe in the wreckage.

944
01:38:39,962 --> 01:38:44,383
"Oh, look. Timmy's shoe.
He's gonna need his shoe. "

945
01:38:46,969 --> 01:38:51,598
And she walks over to it,
reaches down to pick it up.

946
01:38:58,981 --> 01:39:02,401
Ted... Ted wanted to stop her.

947
01:39:08,991 --> 01:39:14,079
Talk about turned to stone.

948
01:39:16,331 --> 01:39:19,835
I couldn't move. I couldn't even speak.

949
01:39:37,019 --> 01:39:40,606
And that was when Ted allowed
his wife to discover...

950
01:39:40,689 --> 01:39:45,319
that her younger son's
shoe was attached...

951
01:39:48,322 --> 01:39:50,824
to a leg.

952
01:39:53,243 --> 01:39:59,208
And that was when Marion realized
that Timmy was gone... too.

953
01:40:04,713 --> 01:40:07,799
And that...

954
01:40:07,883 --> 01:40:11,094
that is the end of the story.

955
01:40:42,668 --> 01:40:45,671
I hired you, Eddie, because
you look like Thomas.

956
01:40:47,965 --> 01:40:50,509
I gave her you.

957
01:40:58,892 --> 01:41:01,395
See you in the morning, Eddie.

958
01:41:37,556 --> 01:41:41,602
It's Eduardo. What's Eduardo doing here?

959
01:41:42,644 --> 01:41:45,606
I don't know. Maybe Mrs.
Vaughn hired him to kill you.

960
01:41:45,606 --> 01:41:48,442
No, no. Not... Not Eduardo.

961
01:41:49,443 --> 01:41:54,156
You don't see her out there anywhere, do
you? She's not in the cab or in the back.

962
01:41:54,198 --> 01:41:58,076
Maybe she's lying underneath the truck.

963
01:41:58,160 --> 01:42:01,705
- I'm being serious, for Chrissake.
- So am I.

964
01:42:05,834 --> 01:42:11,215
Why... Why don't you go out
there and, um, see what he wants?

965
01:42:11,298 --> 01:42:14,801
Not me. I've been fired.

966
01:42:14,927 --> 01:42:18,347
Oh, for Chrissake. What?

967
01:42:19,348 --> 01:42:21,850
Wha...

968
01:42:21,934 --> 01:42:25,312
At least go with me then.
I can't go out there alone.

969
01:42:25,354 --> 01:42:27,898
Mrs. Vaughn fired me.
Eduardo, Eduardo, Eduardo.

970
01:42:27,940 --> 01:42:30,359
Let me make sure I understand you.

971
01:42:30,359 --> 01:42:33,612
You think you saved my life,
and this cost you your job?

972
01:42:33,654 --> 01:42:37,533
Yes, I did save your life, and it
did cost me my job. Well, Eduardo,

973
01:42:37,574 --> 01:42:41,203
I play squash regularly, and
I'm pretty fleet of foot, um,

974
01:42:41,286 --> 01:42:43,789
but I do... I do appreciate
your brave warning.

975
01:42:43,872 --> 01:42:49,044
How much money are we talking about exactly?
I'm not here for a "hand-down," Mr. Cole.

976
01:42:50,629 --> 01:42:53,549
I was hoping you might
have some work for me.

977
01:42:53,632 --> 01:42:55,634
Ah.

978
01:42:58,387 --> 01:43:01,723
Let me... Let me show you
where I want to put a pool.

979
01:43:02,724 --> 01:43:05,853
I want, uh, more lawn, like
an athletic field, you know?

980
01:43:05,936 --> 01:43:08,856
Just, uh, pretty big. You
want some lines painted on it?

981
01:43:08,897 --> 01:43:12,985
No, no. Just the size
of an athletic field.

982
01:43:13,110 --> 01:43:17,239
Wow. That's a lotta lawn.
A lotta mowin'. All right.

983
01:43:17,281 --> 01:43:20,951
And a lot of fertilizers. Yeah.

984
01:43:21,034 --> 01:43:25,247
Well, whatever you say. I'm putting
you in charge. Thank you, Mr. Cole.

985
01:43:25,330 --> 01:43:27,875
What about your wife?

986
01:43:28,917 --> 01:43:34,882
What about her? Oh, uh, does
she work, or what does she do?

987
01:43:34,965 --> 01:43:37,009
Yeah, sure. Sure, she works.

988
01:43:37,050 --> 01:43:41,180
She cooks, she look
after our children. Mmm.

989
01:43:42,264 --> 01:43:45,392
Maybe, uh... Maybe she'd
like to clean my house.

990
01:43:45,434 --> 01:43:49,188
Or maybe she'd like
to cook for me and, uh,

991
01:43:49,271 --> 01:43:52,024
look after my daughter, Ruth.

992
01:43:52,107 --> 01:43:54,026
Sure. I'll ask her. Yeah?

993
01:43:55,152 --> 01:43:58,197
Good. Good. Excellent.

994
01:43:59,281 --> 01:44:03,327
Gotta do something about
these straggly flower beds too.

995
01:44:03,410 --> 01:44:05,913
Oh. You can start today, Eduardo.

996
01:44:05,954 --> 01:44:11,585
You can begin by taking my former assistant
to Orient Point, hmm? Sure. I can do that.

997
01:44:13,003 --> 01:44:16,715
Uh, immediately. Before
breakfast, huh? Yes, sir. Yes, sir.

998
01:44:33,065 --> 01:44:35,943
Well, you're a fairly
good driver, Eddie.

999
01:44:38,195 --> 01:44:42,491
About Marion, there's
another thing you should know.

1000
01:44:43,534 --> 01:44:46,787
Even before the
accident... I mean, even...

1001
01:44:46,912 --> 01:44:50,082
even if there had
never been an accident,

1002
01:44:50,165 --> 01:44:52,084
she still would be difficult.

1003
01:44:54,837 --> 01:44:56,964
I don't believe it.

1004
01:45:01,134 --> 01:45:05,639
About the shoe, it was
a basketball shoe...

1005
01:45:05,681 --> 01:45:08,350
an "AirJordan," I think he called it.

1006
01:45:13,522 --> 01:45:16,400
Specific details, Eddie.

1007
01:45:17,860 --> 01:45:19,862
Specific details.

